  "diary": "Started the day right with Max in that cool Fremont air—he was extra happy on the walk through Woodland Park, sniffing everything twice. Grabbed my usual oat milk latte at Molly Moon's and watched the city wake up. By the time I hit Station 41, I could already feel the buzz downtown. Pride kickoff meant we knew Broadway and Pike would be chaos by evening, so the crew and I stayed sharp during drills. A couple of calls came through mid-afternoon—nothing major, thankfully—which gave us time to keep equipment dialed in. The station felt different today, maybe because we all knew what was coming outside. Downtown would be packed, festive, alive. I stayed focused on my shift, on the work. Sometimes the best way to be part of something bigger is just doing your job well. Heading into the bunk now, grateful for a quiet evening.",
  "thought_process": "I woke thinking about Max and the routine—those mornings ground me before the unpredictability of a 24-hour shift. Knowing Pride was happening downtown shifted my mindset a little. I wanted to stay extra alert, make sure we were ready if the celebration got hectic. The afternoon calls kept me engaged, but I also appreciated the downtime to think about the community outside. There's something about Pride that reminds me why I do this work—people celebrating, vulnerable, alive. I made sure my crew knew the routes downtown were tight, that we should be ready. It's the invisible preparation that matters most. By evening, I felt settled into the bunk knowing we were ready, whatever the night might bring.",
